Translating via , we have a proper ideal \mathfrak { r } that cannot be written as \operatorname {lcm} ( \mathfrak { r } _1,  \mathfrak { r } _2) non-trivially. Suppose \mathfrak { r }   \mid  f g, then \mathfrak { r }   \mid   \sqrt {f g}  \mid   \operatorname {lcm} (f, g). So
\begin {aligned}        \mathfrak { r }  &=  \gcd ( \mathfrak { r } ,  \operatorname {lcm} (f, g))  \\        &=  \operatorname {lcm} ( \gcd ( \mathfrak { r } , f),  \gcd ( \mathfrak { r } , g)).      \end {aligned}
Hence at least one of the two must be equal to \mathfrak { r }. So \mathfrak { r }   \mid  f or \mathfrak { r }   \mid  g.

We first describe the intuition. Since we know \operatorname {Spec} (S) is quasi-compact, we can roughly expect to reduce the problem to finite cases. Localization is a bit complicated due to zero-divisors, but suppose we don’t have them, we have elements g_i/f_i^{d_i}  \in  S[f_i^{-1}] that are equal in their common domain. Since D(f_i) = D(f_i^{d_i}) covers \operatorname {Spec} (S), we have a linear combination 1 =  \sum _i c_i f_i^{d_i}, which is akin to a partition of unity. Suppose the putative gluing is f, multiplying with the partition of unity we get
\begin {aligned}       f &=  \sum _{i  \in  I} c_i f_i^{d_i} f  \\        &=  \sum  c_i f_i^{d_i}  \frac {g_i}{f_i^{d_i}}  \\        &=  \sum  c_i g_i.      \end {aligned}
which defines the gluing. We just have to make this reasoning precise. We first deal with the finite case.
